  1. Data set for the second part is available below. For more information, please visit https://www.kaggle.com/rohan0301/unsupervised-learning-on-country-data

  • Variables are:

    • country: Name of the country
    • child_mort: Death of children under 5 years of age per 1000 live births
    • exports: Exports of goods and services per capita. Given as %age of the GDP per capita
    • health: Total health spending per capita. Given as %age of GDP per capita
    • imports: Imports of goods and services per capita. Given as %age of the GDP per capita
    • Income: Net income per person
    • Inflation: The measurement of the annual growth rate of the Total GDP
    • life_expec: The average number of years a new born child would live if the current mortality patterns are to remain the same
    • total_fer: The number of children that would be born to each woman if the current age-fertility rates remain the same
    • gdpp:The GDP per capita. Calculated as the Total GDP divided by the total population.

Part I: Text Mining (45 points total)

  1. (10 points) Explain why we do text mining, i.e., what insights we can gain by sentiment analysis or topic modeling this particular data. Be specific to the data in hand.

Text mining is a method of analyzing a large dataset in investigating hidden information. These details help us in answering issues such as why we have a specific feeling in a given tweet, as well as grouping tweets into distinct categories. The ultimate outcomes of text analysis are unaffected by our emotions or decisions.

Sentiment analysis or topic modelling is a method which helps us to group text into different topics and help us to find out the associated sentiment like is it positive or negative or neutral.Doing sentiment analysis in the given tweet helps us to find the opinion of public about various topics.

  1. (10 points) Data prep:
  • Tokenize the data set by word and remove stop words.
  • Arrange the words in descending order by frequency. Based on the most frequent words, do you need to add more words to stop words? Why/Why not?

Yes, additional stopwords are needed since words like twitpic.com,tinyurl.com,lt,quot,,bgt,gt,mitchelmusso,xx make little sense and are often used.

  • If necessary anti_join the new stop words. Visualize the word counts. Did you need to filter by frequency, or look at some top words? Why/Why not? What does this plot tell you?

Yes, I utilized the top 30 terms to discover the most often used words. It will give all words if it is not filtered, which will make it congested. Looking at the narrative, I realized that more terms like http and twitter needed to be removed. People seem to be tweeting more about how their day is going based on the top 30 terms. How they felt on a given day, as well as their concerns and worry. The top three terms are day, Im, and time, indicating that individuals are tweeting about their day.

custom_stop_words <- tribble(
  # Column names should match stop_words
  ~word, ~lexicon,
  "twitpic.com", "CUSTOM",
  "tinyurl.com", "CUSTOM",
  "lt", "CUSTOM",
  "quot", "CUSTOM",
  "", "CUSTOM",
  "bgt", "CUSTOM",
  "gt", "CUSTOM",
  "mitchelmusso", "CUSTOM",
  "xx", "CUSTOM",
 "dai", "CUSTOM",
 "amp", "CUSTOM",
)

  1. (10 points) Topic Modeling: Carry out a topic model with \(k\).

    • Why did you choose this particular \(k\)?

My k is 2.

I tried running LDA model with k=3 since my Perplexity graph had the least perplexity at 3.But my LDA topic didnt look conviencing as 3rd topic was almost similar to first two topics. So i decided to go with k=2 which gives me an idea of topics.

- Investigate the beta matrix for your model. What are the top 10 words for each topic?

Explaination given below the plot.

tweet_sentence=data1 %>%
  unnest_tokens(output=sentence, token = "sentences", input = content)
tweet_tokens = tweet_sentence %>%
  unnest_tokens(output = word, token = "words", input=sentence) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>%
  anti_join(custom_stop_words)%>%
  anti_join(custom_stop_words1)%>% 
  mutate(word = wordStem(word))

perplexity(ap_lda)
## [1] 3760.049
samp_size=floor(.9*nrow(tweet_matrix))
set.seed(1234)
train_i=sample(nrow(tweet_matrix), size=samp_size)
train_lda=tweet_matrix[train_i,]
test_lda=tweet_matrix[-train_i,]


values=c()
for(i in c(2:8)){
  lda_model=LDA(train_lda, k=i, control=list(seed=1234))
  values =c(values, perplexity(lda_model, newdata=test_lda))
} 
plot(c(2:8), values, main="Perplexityfor k",
     xlab="Number of Topics", ylab="perplexity")

Part II: Unsupervised Data (40 points total)

  1. (10 points) Explain why we do clustering, i.e., what insights we can gain by clustering this particular data. Be specific to the data in hand.

In cluster analysis, we attempt to group objects with similar traits and features together,Here we are trying to group countries together based on the information given to us so that larger set of objects is divided into smaller sets of objects. The objects in a subset are more similar to other objects in that set than to objects in other sets. Clustering helps to categories the countries into different groups based on the given feautres. Some of the factors such as socio economic and health will help us to determine the overall development of country.

  1. (10 points) Use a k-means or k-medoids clustering algorithm.

    • What is your optimal k?

The optimal k is 3

- How did you choose this k?

The Elbow technique / WSS Gap statistic recommended k = 3, which I thought was more meaningful than k = 5.

- What distance measure you used?

I used Euclidean Distance as I decided to go with default distance.

- Are there any benefits or disadvantages of using the algorithm you chose over the other?

Advantages of using K-mean is simple to implement and computationally faster especially with large data sets
